# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: privacy-engineering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:privacy-engineering/data-anonymization] In the context of medical data, anonymized data refers to data from which the patient cannot be identified by the recipient of the information.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-anonymization] The name, address, and full postcode must be removed, together with any other information which, in conjunction with other data held by or disclosed to the recipient, could identify the patient.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-anonymization] There will always be a risk that anonymized data may not stay anonymous over time.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-anonymization] Pairing the anonymized dataset with other data, clever techniques and raw power are some of the ways previously anonymous data sets have become de-anonymized; The data subjects are no longer anonymous.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-anonymization] De-anonymization is the reverse process in which anonymous data is cross-referenced with other data sources to re-identify the anonymous data source.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-anonymization] Generalization and perturbation are the two popular anonymization approaches for relational data.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-anonymization] The process of obscuring data with the ability to re-identify it later is also called pseudonymization and is one way companies can store data in a way that is HIPAA compliant.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-anonymization] However, according to ARTICLE 29 DATA PROTECTION WORKING PARTY, Directive 95/46/EC refers to anonymisation in Recital 26 "signifies that to anonymise any data, the data must be stripped of sufficient elements such that the data subject can no longer be identified.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-anonymization] More precisely, that data must be processed in such a way that it can no longer be used to identify a natural person by using “all the means likely reasonably to be used” by either the controller or a third party.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-anonymization] An important factor is that the processing must be irreversible.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-anonymization] The Directive does not clarify how such a de-identification process should or could be performed.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-anonymization] The focus is on the outcome: that data should be such as not to allow the data subject to be identified via “all” “likely” and “reasonable” means.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-anonymization] Reference is made to codes of conduct as a tool to set out possible anonymisation mechanisms as well as retention in a form in which identification of the data subject is “no longer possible”.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-anonymization] There are five types of data anonymization operations: generalization, suppression, anatomization, permutation, and perturbation.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-anonymization] The European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) requires that stored data on people in the EU undergo either anonymization or a pseudonymization process.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-anonymization] According to the EDPS and AEPD, no one, including the data controller, should be able to re-identify data subjects in a properly anonymized dataset.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-anonymization] Research by data scientists at Imperial College in London and UCLouvain in Belgium, as well as a ruling by Judge Michal Agmon-Gonen of the Tel Aviv District Court, highlight the shortcomings of "Anonymisation" in today's big data world.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-anonymization] Anonymisation reflects an outdated approach to data protection that was developed when the processing of data was limited to isolated (siloed) applications, prior to the popularity of big data processing involving the widespread sharing and combining of data.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-anonymization] Removing identifying metadata from computer files is important for anonymizing them.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-anonymization] Metadata removal tools are useful for achieving this.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-minimization] The principle of data minimization is a global, universal principle of data protection, and can thus be found in almost every legal or regulatory text on data protection/privacy.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-minimization] The OECD Privacy Guidelines refer to the data minimization principle as the *Collection Limitation Principle* (part two, article 7).
[src:privacy-engineering/data-minimization] The data minimization principle is the second of the six fundamental privacy principles set forth in the General Data Protection Regulation and the UK GDPR.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-minimization] The Swiss *Federal Law on Federal Act on Data Protection* (FADP) includes data minimisation as an aspect of data protection by design and data protection by default.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-minimization] The APEC Privacy Framework includes the data minimization principle, referred to as the *Collection Limitation* principle, as principle III.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-minimization] The Canadian Personal Information Protection and Electronic Documents Act (PIPEDA) includes the principle as *Principle 4 - Limiting Collection*.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-minimization] The American Data Privacy and Protection Act (ADPPA), a United States proposed federal online privacy bill that was not enacted, included data minimisation as a main principle.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-minimization] Since the ADPPA, data minimization has become a highly contested issue in U.S. state privacy legislation, culminating in the Maryland Online Data Privacy Act (MODPA) including ADPPA-inspired data minimization requirements in 2024.
[src:privacy-engineering/data-minimization] The American Privacy Rights Act (APRA), a comprehensive data privacy law proposed in April 2024 in the United States, includes a section on data minimisation.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Various types of personal information often come under privacy concerns.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Privacy concerns exist wherever personally identifiable information or other sensitive information is collected, stored, used, and finally destroyed or deleted – in digital form or otherwise.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Improper or non-existent disclosure control can be the root cause for privacy issues.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Informed consent mechanisms including privacy policies and dynamic consent are important in communicating to data subjects the different uses of their personally identifiable information.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Warren II and Louis Brandeis published "The Right to Privacy", an article explaining "the right to be let alone," which helped establish a right to privacy in the United States.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Their guidelines set the foundation for how privacy can be understood in terms of personal data, and influenced the development of the privacy laws of the United States.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] In the United States, the Privacy Act of 1974 represented an achievement in information privacy law.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The law set a Code of Fair Information Practice to govern how federal agencies collect personal information and data.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] After the Watergate and COINTELPRO scandals involving illegal government use of surveillance, this privacy law was intended to help restore public trust in the government.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The Act allowed a person to have the right to access information about themselves and know how their information would be used.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The growth of the internet's popularity in the early 2000s presented different privacy concerns as many companies and organizations began to collect user's personal data.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Scholars such as Daniel Solove explained the importance of informed consent.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] In 2018, the Facebook–Cambridge Analytica data scandal introduced new privacy risks to the public.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] A consulting firm called Cambridge Analytica collected personal user data from over 85 million Facebook users without informed consent.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The data collected was used to assist in politically targeted ads during the 2016 U.S. presidential election.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] This resulted in the United States Federal Trade Commission fining Facebook $5 billion.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The Cambridge Analytica scandal influenced new legislation such as the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Information about a person's financial transactions, including the amount of assets, positions held in stocks or funds, outstanding debts, and purchases can be sensitive.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] If criminals gain access to information such as a person's accounts or credit card numbers, that person could become the victim of fraud or identity theft.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Information about a person's purchases can reveal a great deal about that person's history, such as places they have visited, whom they have contact with, products they have used, their activities and habits, or medications they have used.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] In some cases, corporations may use this information to target individuals with marketing customized towards those individual's personal preferences, which that person may or may not approve.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The ability to control the information one reveals about oneself over the internet and who can access that information has become a growing concern.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] These concerns include whether email can be stored or read by third parties without consent or whether third parties can continue to track the websites that someone visited.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Another concern is whether websites one visits can collect, store, and possibly share personally identifiable information about users.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The advent of various search engines and the use of data mining created a capability for data about individuals to be collected and combined from a wide variety of sources very easily.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] AI facilitated creating inferential information about individuals and groups based on such enormous amounts of collected data, transforming the information economy.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The FTC has provided a set of guidelines that represent widely accepted concepts concerning fair information practices in an electronic marketplace, called the Fair Information Practice Principles.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] But these have been critiqued for their insufficiency in the context of AI-enabled inferential information.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The same applies to any kind of traffic generated on the Internet, including web browsing, instant messaging, and others.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] In order not to give away too much personal information, emails can be encrypted and browsing of webpages as well as other online activities can be done anonymously via anonymizers, or by open source distributed anonymizers, so-called mix networks.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Nym and I2P are examples of well-known mix nets.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] With social media and e-commerce sites being used more frequently, there are more potential openings for stealing consumer's data.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Companies can see which types of products consumers like to purchase and can use targeted ads to try to make people purchase more items thinking that this is what they will want to purchase.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] However, sometimes this type of data is used without explicit consent.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Users are unaware of all of the personal information that is collected about them.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Cookies track browsing data and location settings show where a person is based out of, and can show shops or products that are physically located near someone.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] These combined that be a big safety and privacy issue for users if their data is not being stored safely.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] With laws like the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA), people's data can be protected and they asked for explicit consent before using said data.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Globally, many nations are trying to implement similar clauses to protect consumers.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Email is not the only internet content with privacy concerns.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] In an age where increasing amounts of information are online, social networking sites pose additional privacy challenges.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] People may be tagged in photos or have valuable information exposed about themselves either by choice or unexpectedly by others, referred to as participatory surveillance.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Data about location can also be accidentally published, for example, when someone posts a picture with a store as a background.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Caution should be exercised when posting information online.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Social networks vary in what they allow users to make private and what remains publicly accessible.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Without strong security settings in place and careful attention to what remains public, a person can be profiled by searching for and collecting disparate pieces of information, leading to cases of cyberstalking or reputation damage.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Cookies are used on websites so that users may allow the website to retrieve some information from the user's internet, but they usually do not mention what the data being retrieved is.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] In 2018, the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) passed a regulation that forces websites to visibly disclose to consumers their information privacy practices, referred to as cookie notices.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] This was issued to give consumers the choice of what information about their behavior they consent to letting websites track; however, its effectiveness is controversial.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Some websites may engage in deceptive practices such as placing cookie notices in places on the page that are not visible or only giving consumers notice that their information is being tracked but not allowing them to change their privacy settings.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Apps like Instagram and Facebook collect user data for a personalized app experience; however, they track user activity on other apps, which jeopardizes users' privacy and data.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] By controlling how visible these cookie notices are, companies can discreetly collect data, giving them more power over consumers.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] In the United Kingdom in 2012, the Education Secretary Michael Gove described the National Pupil Database as a "rich dataset" whose value could be "maximised" by making it more openly accessible, including to private companies.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] An example of a data request that Gove indicated had been rejected in the past, but might be possible under an improved version of privacy regulations, was for "analysis on sexual exploitation".
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] This describes the ability to control what information one reveals about oneself over cable television, and who can access that information.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] For example, third parties can track IP TV programs someone has watched at any given time.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Within academia, Institutional Review Boards function to assure that adequate measures are taken to ensure both the privacy and confidentiality of human subjects in research.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] When an individual or group of people steal consumer's data it is considered a breach of data.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] It is a common threat to one's information privacy.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] This includes information such as names, date of birth, credit card information, and social security numbers.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] These types of data breaches can happen when companies do not have the most current or secure infrastructure to secure and encrypt data.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] A small gap can open data to being leaked from outsiders.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] It should also be noted that breaches can happen from inside employees exposing information too.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Companies are investing time in teaching about suspicious activity and using multi factor authentication systems.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] On a federal level in Europe, governments are now mandating that companies report breaches in a timely manner.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] In America HIPAA functions in a similar way and notifies patients when data has been exposed With types of guidelines in place, companies and countries are working to protect personal information and explain how personal data can and should be used.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Laws surrounding information privacy are important for protecting information globally.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] This includes laws that ensure data is collected with consent and is used with transparency .
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] In the continent of Europe, a guideline called The European Union's General Data Protection Regulation requires everyone to ask for consent before using consumer data and to limit the amount of data companies need to take from users in general.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The European Union's General Data Protection Regulation has shown success, and has prompted other nations to follow suit.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] For example, the state of California and the country of Canada decided to create and implement their own version of the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] California created the California Privacy Rights Act (CPRA, 2020) and Canada created the PIPEDA (Government of Canada, 2021), both modeling their guidelines on The European Union's General Data Protection Regulation that puts consumer and user data and privacy right's first.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] More broadly, the U.S. collectively is still working on creating a comprehensive program that can protect data within the many sectors of jobs and companies operating out of the U.S.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] However, there are smaller guidelines and policies for each organization.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] For example, HIPAA or Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act protects medical patient data and information This is not on a national level that protects all user data from different types of companies, but in the U.S. there are organization and industry level protections created.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Artificial intelligence can be seen as a hindrance to protecting information privacy as they collect data widely.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] According to the International Association of Privacy Professionals, about 68% of consumers globally express concern about their privacy online with 57% agreeing that AI can be a threat to their data.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] These concerns have intensified as generative AI tools, which learn from data scraped from the web, have become more widely adopted.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] AI privacy concerns can be linked to unregulated data collection methods, opaque algorithms, and data persistence.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Algorithmic opacity means not understanding exactly how and where AI is getting their data and sources from..
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The lack of clear visibility can make it difficult for someone to understand how their information is being found and used.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Data persistence is data existing for an extended period of time online that can also be without consent.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] As of now in the United States there are not any explicit federal laws governing AI in terms of data collection.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Laws such as the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) and Gramm Leach Bliley Act can regulate companies but it excludes AI.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] There are state legislatures being enacted.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The state of Utah in the United States passed the Artificial Intelligence Policy Act in March of 2024.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The White House Office of Science and Technology Policy created the "Blueprint for an AI Bill of Rights" in 2022 which explained frameworks for data privacy and AI and having AI systems collect user consent prior to using their data.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Many researchers have created additional frameworks to address AI and data privacy including data minimization requirements, auditing of AI, and giving users an option to opt out of data collection when using AI.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] As location tracking capabilities of mobile devices are advancing (location-based services), problems related to user privacy arise.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Location data is among the most sensitive data currently being collected.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] A list of potentially sensitive professional and personal information that could be inferred about an individual knowing only their mobility trace was published in 2009 by the Electronic Frontier Foundation.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] These include the movements of a competitor sales force, attendance of a particular church or an individual's presence in a motel, or at an abortion clinic.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] A recent MIT study by de Montjoye et al. showed that four spatio-temporal points, approximate places and times, are enough to uniquely identify 95% of 1.5 million people in a mobility database.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The study further shows that these constraints hold even when the resolution of the dataset is low.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Therefore, even coarse or blurred datasets provide little anonymity to the person.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] People may not wish for their medical records to be revealed to others due to the confidentiality and sensitivity of what the information could reveal about their health.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] For example, they might be concerned that it might affect their insurance coverage or employment.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Or, it may be because they would not wish for others to know about any medical or psychological conditions or treatments that would bring embarrassment upon themselves.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Revealing medical data could also reveal other details about one's personal life.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Physicians and psychiatrists in many cultures and countries have standards for doctor–patient relationships, which include maintaining confidentiality.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] In some cases, the physician–patient privilege is legally protected.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] These practices are in place to protect the dignity of patients, and to ensure that patients feel free to reveal complete and accurate information required for them to receive the correct treatment.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] To view the United States' laws on governing privacy of private health information, see HIPAA and the HITECH Act.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The Australian law is the Privacy Act 1988 Australia as well as state-based health records legislation.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Children's online privacy is subject to legal protections in many ways.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] In the United States, the Children's Online Privacy Protection Act of 1998 monitors the collection of personal information of children under 13 years of age The law specifically states that website operators must receive parental consent before collecting personal data of children.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The Children's Online Privacy Protection Act of 1998 applies to websites, apps, and all internet based devices that are geared towards children or know that they are collecting data from children under the age of thirteen.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Violating this law can result in penalties up to $43,792 per violation as it is enforced by the Federal Trade Commission.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Additionally, there are state attorneys general that enforce this law.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The Federal Trade Commission has continued to update the Children's Online Privacy Protection Act to meet the current update of emerging technology.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] There was an amendment made in 2013 that expanded the categories of personal information to include persistent identifiers, geolocation data, and any media with a child's description.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The Federal Trade Commisision opened another review of the Children Online Privacy Protection Act in 2019 as well in order to monitor new technologies due to children utilizing mobile devices.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Some have noted that the Children's Online Privacy Protection Act does have its limitations.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The law at this time does not prevent children from accessing inappropriate content or lying about their age.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Moreover, there have been some doubts regarding how comprehensive the Children's Online Privacy Protection Act with educational technology.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Political privacy has been a concern since voting systems emerged in ancient times.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The secret ballot is the simplest and most widespread measure to ensure that political views are not known to anyone other than the voters themselves—it is nearly universal in modern democracy and considered to be a basic right of citizenship.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] In fact, even where other rights of privacy do not exist, this type of privacy very often does.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] There are several forms of voting fraud or privacy violations possible with the use of digital voting machines.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The legal protection of the right to privacy in general – and of data privacy in particular – varies greatly around the world.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Laws and regulations related to Privacy and Data Protection are constantly changing; it is seen as important to keep abreast of any changes in the law and to continually reassess compliance with data privacy and security regulations.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Data protection laws across the globe aim to secure personal information and safeguard individual privacy in a digital era.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) sets a high benchmark, emphasizing consent, transparency, and robust accountability by imposing strict penalties.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Many countries adopt similar principles, mandating that organizations implement effective security measures, respect user rights, and notify breaches.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] In regions such as North America, Asia, and Oceania, data protection frameworks vary from sector-specific regulations to comprehensive legislation.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Globally, these laws balance innovation with privacy, ensuring that personal data is appropriately accessible, managed ethically while mitigating misuse and cyber threats.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The United States Department of Commerce created the International Safe Harbor Privacy Principles certification program in response to the 1995 Directive on Data Protection (Directive 95/46/EC) of the European Commission.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Both the United States and the European Union officially state that they are committed to upholding information privacy of individuals, but the former has caused friction between the two by failing to meet the standards of the EU's stricter laws on personal data.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The negotiation of the Safe Harbor program was, in part, to address this long-running issue.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Directive 95/46/EC declares in Chapter IV Article 25 that personal data may only be transferred from the countries in the European Economic Area to countries which provide adequate privacy protection.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Historically, establishing adequacy required the creation of national laws broadly equivalent to those implemented by Directive 95/46/EU.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Although there are exceptions to this blanket prohibition – for example where the disclosure to a country outside the EEA is made with the consent of the relevant individual (Article 26(1)(a)) – they are limited in practical scope.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] As a result, Article 25 created a legal risk to organizations which transfer personal data from Europe to the United States.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The program regulates the exchange of passenger name record information between the EU and the US.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] According to the EU directive, personal data may only be transferred to third countries if that country provides an adequate level of protection.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Some exceptions to this rule are provided, for instance when the controller themself can guarantee that the recipient will comply with the data protection rules.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The European Commission has set up the "Working party on the Protection of Individuals with regard to the Processing of Personal Data," commonly known as the "Article 29 Working Party".
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The Working Party gives advice about the level of protection in the European Union and third countries.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The Working Party negotiated with U.S. representatives about the protection of personal data, the Safe Harbor Principles were the result.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Notwithstanding that approval, the self-assessment approach of the Safe Harbor remains controversial with a number of European privacy regulators and commentators.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The Safe Harbor program addresses this issue in the following way: rather than a blanket law imposed on all organizations in the United States, a voluntary program is enforced by the Federal Trade Commission.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] U.S. organizations which register with this program, having self-assessed their compliance with a number of standards, are "deemed adequate" for the purposes of Article 25.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Personal information can be sent to such organizations from the EEA without the sender being in breach of Article 25 or its EU national equivalents.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The Safe Harbor was approved as providing adequate protection for personal data, for the purposes of Article 25(6), by the European Commission on 26 July 2000.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Under the Safe Harbor, adoptee organizations need to carefully consider their compliance with the *onward transfer obligations*, where personal data originating in the EU is transferred to the US Safe Harbor, and then onward to a third country.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The alternative compliance approach of "binding corporate rules", recommended by many EU privacy regulators, resolves this issue.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] In addition, any dispute arising in relation to the transfer of HR data to the US Safe Harbor must be heard by a panel of EU privacy regulators.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] In July 2007, a new, controversial, Passenger Name Record agreement between the US and the EU was made.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] A short time afterwards, the Bush administration gave exemption for the Department of Homeland Security, for the Arrival and Departure Information System (ADIS) and for the Automated Target System from the 1974 Privacy Act.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] In February 2008, Jonathan Faull, the head of the EU's Commission of Home Affairs, complained about the US bilateral policy concerning PNR.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The US had signed in February 2008 a memorandum of understanding (MOU) with the Czech Republic in exchange of a visa waiver scheme, without concerting before with Brussels.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] The tensions between Washington and Brussels are mainly caused by a lesser level of data protection in the US, especially since foreigners do not benefit from the US Privacy Act of 1974.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] Other countries approached for bilateral MOU included the United Kingdom, Estonia, Germany and Greece.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] There are techniques to improve privacy, privacy-enhancing technologies, and privacy software tools.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] People building and updating systems can use privacy by design and privacy engineering strategies and techniques.
[src:privacy-engineering/information-privacy] For example, by converting data into a non-readable format, encryption prevents unauthorized access.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] The abbreviation PII is widely used in the United States, but the phrase it abbreviates has four common variants based on *personal* or *personally*, and *identifiable* or *identifying*.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Not all are equivalent, and for legal purposes the effective definitions vary depending on the jurisdiction and the purposes for which the term is being used.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Under European Union and United Kingdom data protection regimes, which centre primarily on the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), the term "personal data" is significantly broader, and determines the scope of the regulatory regime.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Personal data is defined under the GDPR as "any information which [is] related to an identified or identifiable natural person".
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] The IP address of an Internet subscriber may be classed as personal data.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] The concept of PII has become prevalent as information technology and the Internet have made it easier to collect PII leading to a profitable market in collecting and reselling PII.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] PII can also be exploited by criminals to stalk or steal the identity of a person, or to aid in the planning of criminal acts.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] As a response to these threats, many website privacy policies specifically address the gathering of PII, and lawmakers such as the European Parliament have enacted a series of legislative acts such as the GDPR to limit the distribution and accessibility of PII.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Serious confusion arises around whether PII means information which is identifiable (that is, can be associated with a person) or identifying (that is, associated uniquely with a person, such that the PII *identifies* them).
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] In prescriptive data privacy regimes such as the US federal Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA), PII items have been specifically defined.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] In broader data protection regimes such as the GDPR, personal data is defined in a non-prescriptive principles-based way.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Information that might not count as PII under HIPAA can be personal data for the purposes of GDPR.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] For this reason, "PII" is typically deprecated internationally.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] In the EU rules, there has been a more specific notion that the data subject can potentially be identified through additional processing of other attributes—quasi- or pseudo-identifiers.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] A simple example of this distinction: the color name "red" by itself is *not* personal data, but that same value stored as part of a person's record as their "favorite color" *is* personal data; it is the connection to the person that makes it personal data, not (as in PII) the value itself.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] The concept of information combination given in the SB1386 definition is key to correctly distinguishing PII, as defined by OMB, from "personal information", as defined by SB1386.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Information, such as a name, that lacks context cannot be said to be SB1386 "personal information", but it must be said to be PII as defined by OMB.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] For example, the name "John Smith" has no meaning in the current context and is therefore not SB1386 "personal information", but it is PII.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] A Social Security Number (SSN) without a name or some other associated identity or context information is not SB1386 "personal information", but it is PII.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] For example, the SSN 078-05-1120 by itself is PII, but it is not SB1386 "personal information".
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] However the combination of a valid name with the correct SSN is SB1386 "personal information".
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] The combination of a name with a context may also be considered PII; for example, if a person's name is on a list of patients for an HIV clinic.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] However, it is not necessary for the name to be combined with a context in order for it to be PII.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] The reason for this distinction is that bits of information such as names, although they may not be sufficient by themselves to make an identification, may later be combined with other information to identify persons and expose them to harm.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] The scope of the term "sensitive personal data" varies by jurisdiction.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] In the UK, personal health data is treated as "sensitive" and in need of additional data protection measures.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] According to the OMB, in the United States it is not always the case that PII is "sensitive", and context may be taken into account in deciding whether certain PII is or is not sensitive.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] When a person wishes to remain anonymous, descriptions of them will often employ several of the above, such as "a 34-year-old white male who works at Target".
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Information can still be *private*, in the sense that a person may not wish for it to become publicly known, without being personally identifiable.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Moreover, sometimes multiple pieces of information, none sufficient by itself to uniquely identify an individual, may uniquely identify a person when combined; this is one reason that multiple pieces of evidence are usually presented at criminal trials.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] It has been shown that, in 1990, 87% of the population of the United States could be uniquely identified by gender, ZIP code, and full date of birth.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] In hacker and Internet slang, the practice of finding and releasing such information is called "doxing".
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] It is sometimes used to deter collaboration with law enforcement.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] On occasion, the doxing can trigger an arrest, particularly if law enforcement agencies suspect that the "doxed" individual may panic and disappear.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] It appears that this definition is significantly broader than the Californian example given above, and thus that Australian privacy law may cover a broader category of data and information than in some US law.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] The term "PII" is not used in Australian privacy law.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] European Union data protection law does not use the concept of personally identifiable information, and its scope is instead determined by the non-synonymous, wider concept of "personal data".
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Further examples can be found on the EU privacy website.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] On 1 June 2023, the Hong Kong Office of the Privacy Commissioner for Personal Data published an investigation report on a data breach involving the unauthorised access of a credit reference database platform.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] The Report highlights the need for organizations to take adequate steps to protect personal data as the mere imposition of contractual obligations and policies is insufficient if such obligations and policies are not effective or are not enforced.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] The Report also clarifies that credit data is a form of "sensitive" personal data.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] The twelve Information Privacy Principles of the Privacy Act 1993 apply.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] New Zealand enacted the Privacy Act in 2020 to promote and protect individual privacy.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] The Federal Act on Data Protection of 19 June 1992 (in force since 1993) has set up a protection of privacy by prohibiting virtually any processing of personal data which is not expressly authorized by the data subjects.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] The protection is subject to the authority of the Federal Data Protection and Information Commissioner.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Additionally, any person may ask in writing a company managing data files to correct or delete any personal data.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] The company must respond within thirty days.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] One of the primary focuses of the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) is to protect a patient's Protected Health Information (PHI), which is similar to PII.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Senate proposed the Privacy Act of 2005, which attempted to strictly limit the display, purchase, or sale of PII without the person's consent.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Similarly, the (proposed) Anti-Phishing Act of 2005 attempted to prevent the acquiring of PII through phishing.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] U.S. lawmakers have paid special attention to the social security number because it can be easily used to commit identity theft.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] The (proposed) Social Security Number Protection Act of 2005 and (proposed) Identity Theft Prevention Act of 2005 each sought to limit the distribution of an individual's social security number.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Additional U.S.-specific personally identifiable information includes, but is not limited to, I-94 records, Medicaid ID numbers, and Internal Revenue Service (I.R.S.) documentation.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Exclusivity of personally identifiable information affiliated with the U.S. highlights national data security concerns and the influence of personally identifiable information in U.S. federal data management systems.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) is a physical sciences laboratory, and a non-regulatory agency of the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Its mission is to promote innovation and industrial competitiveness.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] The following are less often used to distinguish individual identity, because they are traits shared by many people.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] However, they are potentially PII, because they may be combined with other personal information to identify an individual.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] In forensics, particularly the identification and prosecution of criminals, personally identifiable information is critical in establishing evidence in criminal procedure.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Personal data is a key component of online identity and can be exploited by individuals.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] For instance, data can be altered and used to create fake documents, hijack mail boxes and phone calls or harass people, as occurred in 2019 to a customer of the EE mobile phone operator in the UK.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Another category can be referred to as financial identity theft, which usually entails bank account and credit card information being stolen, and then being used or sold.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Personal data can also be used to create fake online identities, including fake accounts and profiles (which can be referred as identity cloning or identity fraud) for celebrities to gather data from other users more easily.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Even individuals can be concerned, especially for personal purposes (this is more widely known as sockpuppetry).
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] The most critical information, such as one's password, date of birth, ID documents or social security number, can be used to log in to different websites (e.g. password reuse and account verification) to gather more information and access more content.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Also, several agencies ask for discretion on subjects related to their work, for the safety of their employees.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] For this reason, the United States Department of Defense (DoD) has strict policies controlling release of personally identifiable information of DoD personnel.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Many intelligence agencies have similar policies, sometimes to the point where employees do not disclose to their friends that they work for the agency.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Similar identity protection concerns exist for witness protection programs, women's shelters, and victims of domestic violence and other threats.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Personal information removal services work by identifying and requesting data brokers to delete the personal information of their clients.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] This process can be manual or fully automated, but it is nevertheless complex because it involves dealing with numerous data brokers, each with different policies and procedures for data removal.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Companies offering personal information removal also face some issues.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] They struggle to ensure comprehensive data removal as new data brokers emerge and existing ones don’t always comply with removal requests.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Most of them are also limited to certain regions or countries.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] During the second half of the 20th century, the digital revolution introduced "privacy economics", or the trade of personal data.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] The value of data can change over time and over different contexts.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Disclosing data can reverse information asymmetry, though the costs of doing so can be unclear.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] In relation to companies, consumers often have "imperfect information regarding when their data is collected, with what purposes, and with what consequences".
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] In the mid-1990s, Varian retook the Chicago Boys approach and added a new externality, stating that the consumer would not always have perfect information on how their own data would be used.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Laudon developed a model in which individuals own their data and have the ability to sell it as a product.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] He believed that such a system should not be regulated, to create a free market.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] In the 2000s, researchers worked on price discrimination (Taylor, 2004), two-sided markets (Cornière, 2011) and marketing strategies (Anderson and de Palma, 2012).
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] The theories became complex, and showed that the impact of privacy on the economy highly depended on the context.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Sources, usually Internet-based since the 1990s, may include census and electoral roll records, social networking sites, court reports and purchase histories.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] The information from data brokers may be used in background checks used by employers and housing.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] There are varying regulations around the world limiting the collection of information on individuals; privacy laws vary.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] In the United States there is no federal regulation protection for the consumer from data brokers, although some states have begun enacting laws individually.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] In the European Union, GDPR serves to regulate data brokers' operations.
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Some data brokers report to have large numbers of population data or "data attributes".
[src:privacy-engineering/personally-identifiable-information] Acxiom purports to have data from 2.5 billion different people.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Recent developments in computer science and data engineering, such as support for encoding privacy in data and the availability and quality of Privacy-Enhancing Technologies (PET's) partly offset those critiques and help to make the principles feasible in real-world settings.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The European GDPR regulation incorporates privacy by design.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The privacy by design framework was developed by Ann Cavoukian, Information and Privacy Commissioner of Ontario, following her joint work with the Dutch Data Protection Authority and the Netherlands Organisation for Applied Scientific Research in 1995.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] In 2009, the Information and Privacy Commissioner of Ontario co-hosted an event, *Privacy by Design: The Definitive Workshop*, with the Israeli Law, Information and Technology Authority at the 31st International Conference of Data Protection and Privacy Commissioners (2009).
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] In 2010 the framework achieved international acceptance when the International Assembly of Privacy Commissioners and Data Protection Authorities unanimously passed a resolution on privacy by design recognising it as an international standard at their annual conference.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Among other commitments, the commissioners resolved to promote privacy by design as widely as possible and foster the incorporation of the principle into policy and legislation.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The principles have been cited in over five hundred articles referring to the *Privacy by Design in Law, Policy and Practice* white paper by Ann Cavoukian.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The privacy by design approach is characterized by proactive rather than reactive measures.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] It anticipates and prevents privacy invasive events before they happen.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design does not wait for privacy risks to materialize, nor does it offer remedies for resolving privacy infractions once they have occurred — it aims to prevent them from occurring.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] In short, privacy by design comes before-the-fact, not after.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design seeks to deliver the maximum degree of privacy by ensuring that personal data are automatically protected in any given IT system or business practice.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] If an individual does nothing, their privacy still remains intact.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] No action is required on the part of the individual to protect their privacy — it is built into the system, by default.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design is embedded into the design and architecture of IT systems as well as business practices.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] It is not bolted on as an add-on, after the fact.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The result is that privacy becomes an essential component of the core functionality being delivered.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Privacy is integral to the system without diminishing functionality.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design seeks to accommodate all legitimate interests and objectives in a positive-sum “win-win” manner, not through a dated, zero-sum approach, where unnecessary trade-offs are made.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design avoids the pretense of false dichotomies, such as privacy versus security, demonstrating that it is possible to have both.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design, having been embedded into the system prior to the first element of information being collected, extends securely throughout the entire lifecycle of the data involved — strong security measures are essential to privacy, from start to finish.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] This ensures that all data are securely retained, and then securely destroyed at the end of the process, in a timely fashion.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Thus, privacy by design ensures cradle-to-grave, secure lifecycle management of information, end-to-end.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design seeks to assure all stakeholders that whatever business practice or technology involved is in fact operating according to the stated promises and objectives, subject to independent verification.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The component parts and operations remain visible and transparent, to users and providers alike.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Above all, privacy by design requires architects and operators to keep the interests of the individual uppermost by offering such measures as strong privacy defaults, appropriate notice, and empowering user-friendly options.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) approved the Committee on Consumer Policy (COPOLCO) proposal for a new ISO standard: *Consumer Protection: Privacy by Design for Consumer Goods and Services* (ISO/PC317).
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The standard will aim to specify the design process to provide consumer goods and services that meet consumers’ domestic processing privacy needs as well as the personal privacy requirements of data protection.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The standard has the UK as secretariat with thirteen participating members and twenty observing members.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The Standards Council of Canada (SCC) is one of the participating members and has established a mirror Canadian committee to ISO/PC317.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The OASIS Privacy by Design Documentation for Software Engineers (PbD-SE) Technical Committee provides a specification to operationalize privacy by design in the context of software engineering.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design, like security by design, is a normal part of the software development process and a risk reduction strategy for software engineers.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The PbD-SE specification translates the PbD principles to conformance requirements within software engineering tasks and helps software development teams to produce artifacts as evidence of PbD principle adherence.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design originated from privacy-enhancing technologies (PETs) in a joint 1995 report by Ann Cavoukian and John Borking.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] In 2007 the European Commission provided a memo on PETs.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] In 2008 the British Information Commissioner's Office commissioned a report titled *Privacy by Design – An Overview of Privacy Enhancing Technologies*.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] There are many facets to privacy by design.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] There is the technical side like software and systems engineering, administrative elements (e.g. legal, policy, procedural), other organizational controls, and operating contexts.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design evolved from early efforts to express fair information practice principles directly into the design and operation of information and communications technologies.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] In his publication *Privacy by Design: Delivering the Promises* Peter Hustinx acknowledges the key role played by Ann Cavoukian and John Borking, then Deputy Privacy Commissioners, in the joint 1995 publication *Privacy-Enhancing Technologies: The Path to Anonymity*.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] This 1995 report focussed on exploring technologies that permit transactions to be conducted anonymously.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Privacy-enhancing technologies allow online users to protect the privacy of their Personally Identifiable Information (PII) provided to and handled by services or applications.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design evolved to consider the broader systems and processes in which PETs were embedded and operated.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Center for Democracy & Technology (CDT) in *The Role of Privacy by Design in Protecting Consumer Privacy* distinguishes PET from privacy by design noting that “PETs are most useful for users who already understand online privacy risks.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] 4 *Teledienstedatenschutzgesetz* [Teleservices Data Protection Act]) in July 1997.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The new EU General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) includes ‘data protection by design’ and ‘data protection by default’, the second foundational principle of privacy by design.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Canada's Privacy Commissioner included privacy by design in its report on *Privacy, Trust and Innovation – Building Canada's Digital Advantage*.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] In Australia, the Commissioner for Privacy and Data Protection for the State of Victoria (CPDP) has formally adopted privacy by design as a core policy to underpin information privacy management in the Victorian public sector.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The UK Information Commissioner's Office website highlights privacy by design and data protection by design and default.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] In October 2014, the Mauritius Declaration on the Internet of Things was made at the 36th International Conference of Data Protection and Privacy Commissioners and included privacy by design and default.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The Privacy Commissioner for Personal Data, Hong Kong held an educational conference on the importance of privacy by design.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] In the private sector, Sidewalk Toronto commits to privacy by design principles; Brendon Lynch, Chief Privacy Officer at Microsoft, wrote an article called *Privacy by Design at Microsoft*; whilst Deloitte relates certifiably trustworthy to privacy by design.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The privacy by design framework attracted academic debate, particularly following the 2010 International Data Commissioners resolution that provided criticism of privacy by design with suggestions by legal and engineering experts to better understand how to apply the framework into various contexts.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design has been critiqued as "vague" and leaving "many open questions about their application when engineering systems." Suggestions have been made to instead start with and focus on minimizing data, which can be done through security engineering.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Leuven published Engineering Privacy by Design noting that “The design and implementation of privacy requirements in systems is a difficult problem and requires translation of complex social, legal and ethical concerns into systems requirements”.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The principles of privacy by design "remain vague and leave many open questions about their application when engineering systems".
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The authors argue that "starting from data minimization is a necessary and foundational first step to engineer systems in line with the principles of privacy by design".
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] This is partly a more structural problem due to the fact that legal principles are abstract, open-ended with different possible interpretations and exceptions, whereas engineering practices require unambiguous meanings and formal definitions of design concepts.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] In 2011, the Danish National It and Telecom Agency published a discussion paper in which they argued that privacy by design is a key goal for creating digital security models, by extending the concept to "Security by Design".
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The objective is to balance anonymity and surveillance by eliminating identification as much as possible.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Another criticism is that current definitions of privacy by design do not address the methodological aspect of systems engineering, such as using decent system engineering methods, e.g. those which cover the complete system and data life cycle.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] This problem is further exacerbated in the move to networked digital infrastructures initiatives such as the smart city or the Internet of Things.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Whereas privacy by design has mainly been focused on the responsibilities of singular organisations for a certain technology, these initiatives often require the interoperability of many different technologies operated by different organisations.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] This requires a shift from organisational to infrastructural design.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The concept of privacy by design also does not focus on the role of the actual data holder but on that of the system designer.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] This role is not known in privacy law, so the concept of privacy by design is not based on law.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] This, in turn, undermines the trust by data subjects, data holders and policy-makers.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Questions have been raised from science and technology studies of whether privacy by design will change the meaning and practice of rights through implementation in technologies, organizations, standards and infrastructures.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] From a civil society perspective, some have even raised the possibility that a bad use of these design-based approaches can even lead to the danger of bluewashing.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] This refers to the minimal instrumental use by organizations of privacy design without adequate checks, in order to portray themselves as more privacy-friendly than is factually justified.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] It has also been pointed out that privacy by design is similar to voluntary compliance schemes in industries impacting the environment, and thus lacks the teeth necessary to be effective, and may differ per company.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] In addition, the evolutionary approach currently taken to the development of the concept will come at the cost of privacy infringements because evolution implies also letting unfit phenotypes (privacy-invading products) live until they are proven unfit.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Some critics have pointed out that certain business models are built around customer surveillance and data manipulation and therefore voluntary compliance is unlikely.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] In 2013, Rubinstein and Good used Google and Facebook privacy incidents to conduct a counterfactual analysis in order to identify lessons learned of value for regulators when recommending privacy by design.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The first was that “more detailed principles and specific examples” would be more helpful to companies.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The second is that “usability is just as important as engineering principles and practices”.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The third is that there needs to be more work on “refining and elaborating on design principles–both in privacy engineering and usability design”. including efforts to define international privacy standards.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The final lesson learned is that "regulators must do more than merely recommend the adoption and implementation of privacy by design".
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Rubinstein and Good also highlighted that privacy by design could result in applications that exemplified Privacy by Design and their work was well received.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The following sections of this opinion provide an overview of relevant developments and recommend further efforts".
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The European Data Protection Supervisor Giovanni Buttarelli set out the requirement to implement privacy by design in his article.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The European Union Agency for Network and Information Security (ENISA) provided a detailed report *Privacy and Data Protection by Design – From Policy to Engineering* on implementation.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The Summer School on real-world crypto and privacy provided a tutorial on "Engineering Privacy by Design".
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The OWASP Top 10 Privacy Risks Project for web applications that gives hints on how to implement privacy by design in practice.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] The OASIS Privacy by Design Documentation for Software Engineers (PbD-SE) offers a privacy extension/complement to OMG's Unified Modeling Language (UML) and serves as a complement to OASIS’ eXtensible Access Control Mark-up Language (XACML) and Privacy Management Reference Model (PMRM).
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] Privacy by Design guidelines are developed to operationalise some of the high-level privacy-preserving ideas into more granular actionable advice., such as recommendations on how to implement privacy by design into existing (data) systems.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-by-design] However, still the applications of privacy by design guidelines by software developers remains a challenge.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-engineering] In the EU, however, the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) sets the requirements that need to be fulfilled.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-engineering] In the rest of the world, the requirements change depending on local implementations of privacy and data protection laws.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-engineering] While privacy has been developing as a legal domain, privacy engineering has only really come to the fore in recent years as the necessity of implementing said privacy laws in information systems has become a definite requirement to the deployment of such information systems.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-engineering] Privacy engineering involves aspects such as process management, security, ontology and software engineering.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-engineering] The actual application of these derives from necessary legal compliances, privacy policies and 'manifestos' such as Privacy-by-Design.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-engineering] Towards the more implementation levels, privacy engineering employs privacy enhancing technologies to enable anonymisation and de-identification of data.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-engineering] Privacy engineering requires suitable security engineering practices to be deployed, and some privacy aspects can be implemented using security techniques.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-engineering] A privacy impact assessment is another tool within this context and its use does not imply that privacy engineering is being practiced.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-engineering] One area of concern is the proper definition and application of terms such as personal data, personally identifiable information, anonymisation and pseudo-anonymisation which lack sufficient and detailed enough meanings when applied to software, information systems and data sets.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-engineering] Another facet of information system privacy has been the ethical use of such systems with particular concern on surveillance, big data collection, artificial intelligence etc.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-engineering] Some members of the privacy and privacy engineering community advocate for the idea of ethics engineering or reject the possibility of engineering privacy into systems intended for surveillance.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-engineering] Software engineers often encounter problems when interpreting legal norms into current technology.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-engineering] Legal requirements are by nature neutral to technology and will in case of legal conflict be interpreted by a court in the context of the current status of both technology and privacy practice.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-engineering] Despite the lack of a cohesive development of the above areas, courses already exist for the training of privacy engineering.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-engineering] The International Workshop on Privacy Engineering co-located with IEEE Symposium on Security and Privacy provides a venue to address "the gap between research and practice in systematizing and evaluating approaches to capture and address privacy issues while engineering information systems".
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-engineering] A number of approaches to privacy engineering exist.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-engineering] The LINDDUN methodology takes a risk-centric approach to privacy engineering where personal data flows at risk are identified and then secured with privacy controls.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-engineering] Guidance for interpretation of the GDPR has been provided in the GDPR recitals, which have been coded into a decision tool that maps GDPR into software engineering forces with the goal to identify suitable privacy design patterns.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-engineering] One further approach uses eight privacy design strategies - four technical and four administrative strategies - to protect data and to implement data subject rights.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-engineering] Further to this how the above then affect the security classification, risk classification and thus the levels of protection and flow within a system can then the metricised or calculated.
[src:privacy-engineering/privacy-engineering] Privacy is an area dominated by legal aspects but requires implementation using, ostensibly, engineering techniques, disciplines and skills.
